        <h2>The GEO Definition</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>In one line: GEO is the discipline of making a brand the source that generative AI models quote when they answer a question — earned through content structure, entity authority, and technical readiness rather than blue-link rankings.</strong>
          The term applies equally to the British spelling used throughout this guide and the American spelling — generative engine optimization — which dominates search volume due to the US market.
        </p>

        <p>
          The word "generative" refers to the AI's behaviour: rather than retrieving and ranking existing pages, a generative engine creates a new, synthesised response by combining information from multiple sources. The word "optimisation" reflects the practitioner's task: shaping your content, entity presence, and technical setup to be selected and cited within that generated response.
        </p>

        <p>
          GEO is part of the broader AI search landscape that includes <a href="/answer-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">answer engine optimisation (AEO)</a> and traditional SEO. Understanding how these three disciplines relate to each other — and where GEO's definition begins and ends — is the first step in building an effective strategy. For a full practitioner's guide, see <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Generative Engine Optimisation: Complete Guide</a>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The concept was first described in academic research in 2023, as practitioners and researchers began observing that the emergence of AI-powered search surfaces required a distinct optimisation framework — one that could not simply be mapped onto existing SEO or AEO practices. The term "GEO" has since become the dominant label for this discipline within the industry.
        </p>
      </section>

