      <!-- Section 4: Why Definition Matters -->
      <section id="why-definition-matters" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Why Getting the Definition Right Matters</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Misdefining GEO leads to strategies that optimise for the wrong signals — and in a discipline this new, definitional clarity is a competitive advantage.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          The most common definitional error is treating GEO as a synonym for "AI-optimised SEO" — applying traditional keyword and backlink strategies to content, then declaring it "GEO-ready." This approach misses the specific mechanisms that AI citation depends on: entity authority in knowledge bases, content structured for passage extraction, and cross-model visibility testing. Brands that conflate the two disciplines will see their SEO metrics improve while their AI citation rates remain low.
        </p>

        <p>
          A second common error is treating GEO and AEO as identical. AEO is a subset of GEO that focuses on direct-answer extraction — featured snippets, voice answers. GEO encompasses that, but extends to the generative synthesis layer: the fully composed AI responses that ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews produce. These systems use different retrieval mechanisms, different authority signals, and different extraction patterns than the featured-snippet system. Optimising only for AEO leaves the generative layer unaddressed.
        </p>

        <p>
          Getting the definition right also matters for measurement. If you measure GEO success using traditional SEO metrics — ranking position, organic CTR — you will reach incorrect conclusions about your programme's effectiveness. GEO requires its own KPI framework: citation frequency, citation accuracy, AI share of voice, and referral traffic from AI platforms. See our guide to <a href="/generative-search-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative search optimisation</a> for measurement detail.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: RAG Explained -->
      <section id="rag-explained" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>RAG Explained: Why It Is Central to GEO</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is the technical pipeline at the heart of all major AI search platforms, and understanding it is essential to understanding why GEO works the way it does.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          A pure large language model — without retrieval — generates answers based solely on its training data. This creates problems: the training data has a cutoff date, the model may hallucinate facts it is uncertain about, and it cannot attribute claims to specific sources. RAG solves these problems by connecting the LLM to a live retrieval system.
        </p>

        <p>
          When a RAG-powered system receives a query, it first retrieves relevant documents from a web index or curated corpus. It extracts the most relevant passages from those documents. Then it passes those passages to the LLM as context, and the LLM synthesises them into a coherent answer — citing the sources it drew from. This is the pipeline that powers Google AI Overviews, Perplexity, Microsoft Copilot, and most other AI search platforms.
        </p>

        <p>
          GEO targets every stage of this pipeline. At the retrieval stage, entity authority and technical SEO determine whether your page is retrieved at all. At the extraction stage, content structure and declarative sentence patterns determine whether your specific passage is selected. At the synthesis stage, the uniqueness and specificity of your content determines whether you are cited as a distinct source or your information is absorbed into a generic synthesis without attribution.
        </p>

        <p>
          Brands that understand the RAG pipeline optimise differently from brands that treat GEO as a content format exercise. The former build entity authority first, then structure content for passage extraction, then test cross-model citation. The latter write "AI-friendly" content without addressing the upstream signals that determine whether that content ever enters the retrieval pool. For a detailed walkthrough, see <a href="/how-geo-works/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how GEO works</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Entity Explained -->
      <section id="entity-explained" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Is an Entity in GEO?</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>In GEO, an entity is any distinctly identifiable real-world concept — a brand, person, product, technology, or organisation — that AI systems can recognise, define, and link to authoritative knowledge sources.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          AI systems, including the LLMs at the core of generative search, do not evaluate sources the way a human editor would — reading content and assessing its quality. Instead, they rely on structural signals: is this concept (brand, claim, product) connected to recognised entities in my knowledge graph? Does this entity have consistent definitions across Wikipedia, Wikidata, and other authoritative references? If yes, the entity — and content attributed to it — is treated as credible. If not, the content may be retrieved but the brand is unlikely to be explicitly cited.
        </p>

        <p>
          Building entity authority means establishing your brand as a well-defined entity across the knowledge sources that LLMs reference. A Wikipedia article about your brand, a Wikidata record with accurate properties, a verified Google Knowledge Panel, and consistent mentions in reputable industry publications all contribute to entity authority. Schema markup using <code>sameAs</code> properties that link your website entity to these external records reinforces the connection.
        </p>

        <p>
          Entity optimisation is foundational — it must precede content restructuring work. A brand that invests heavily in citable content architecture but lacks entity authority will find that AI models recognise the content but do not attribute it. The attribution step requires trust, and trust is built through entity presence, not content quality alone.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 7: Citation Explained -->
      <section id="citation-explained" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Is a Citation in GEO?</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>An AI citation is an explicit attribution within a generated response that credits a specific source — your brand, your page, or your stated claim — for information included in the AI's answer.</strong>
          AI citations are the primary outcome of a GEO strategy and the core unit of GEO measurement.
        </p>

        <p>
          Citations take different forms across AI platforms. On Perplexity and Microsoft Copilot, citations appear as numbered superscripts within the answer text, each linking to the source page. On Google AI Overviews, sources are displayed in a collapsible citations panel beside or below the generated answer. On ChatGPT with browsing, cited pages appear as footnotes or inline links. The visual presentation varies, but the underlying mechanism — a specific page being credited as a source for a claim — is the same.
        </p>

        <h3>Citation Frequency vs Citation Accuracy</h3>
        <p>
          GEO measurement tracks two citation dimensions. Citation frequency measures how often your brand or page appears in AI answers for your target query set — expressed as a percentage of queries where your brand is cited. Citation accuracy measures whether the AI correctly represents your claims, brand positioning, and data when it does cite you. A high frequency rate with low accuracy — where AI models cite you but misrepresent your offering — can damage brand positioning rather than strengthen it.
        </p>

        <h3>Share of Voice in AI Answers</h3>
        <p>
          Because AI answers typically cite a small number of sources (one to five, depending on the platform and query type), citation share of voice — your brand's citation share relative to competitors across a defined query set — is a more meaningful competitive metric than raw citation count. A brand cited in 60% of relevant queries while competitors collectively account for the remaining 40% has achieved dominant AI share of voice. For services and measurement tools, see <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

